@Bill 
ALOO GOBI is the only way to eat cauliflower, in my opinion. It's a very sad vegetable.

And PANDA CAMs are definitely a thing. There are plenty of live feeds of animals doing animal things out there. Here in Minnesota, we have an eagle cam to spy on our bald eagles.

@Andrzeg
Steve L is correct.
If you do a search for pictures of gas station islands, you will see.

@Andrzej 

We, too, have numbered pumps -- in modern times. But gas station "island" is not a technical or legal term, rather one the consuming public and/or attendant will use. Maybe less commonly so in the era of self-serve gas -- and pump numbers!

For me personally, it's a term that harkens back to the ungainly automobiles and leaded gasoline of my (suburban) youth. Fun clue, once it clicked!

@Michael Hendler 

I’m aware of kitchen islands, as we have one. There is no GAS stove on it or anywhere else, as we have electric, but regardless, most GAS is delivered to the kitchen via the walls of the house. It would be unnecessarily complicated to put it in the island.

All of the major appliances are along the walls of our kitchen because it makes sense to do it that way.  The island is a prep/dining area on top, and storage below. Some islands do have sinks, though, although ours doesn’t.

@Andrzej
No CRAWLSPACEs in Poland, but many, many in California.

Foundations for buildings have to be dug down below the freeze depth.  In Poland, and other places with cold winters, that is deep enough that you end up with a basement.  In California, where I am, and other warm-weather locations, the foundation can be put right on the surface.  Many houses in my neighborhood are built on a cement slab.  Or many have a crawl space just big enough to hold the under-house plumbing and electrical fixtures.  Hence the term crawl space.  One has to crawl on stomach to do any repairs down there.  The one at my house is a little over a meter high.  That makes it easier to crawl on hands and knees.  And our furnace is down there too.

@AudreyLM 
I can relate.

A lot of the slang terms I grew up with are outdated. Now they're AGE LINEs.

@RozzieGrandma 
Lol.  I did manage to get through Last of the Mohicans at some point.  That part of the comment was directed at my cousin, who read the book just before going to see the movie. She should have known better. 
Way back when, there was a little piece in the Times imagining what the title would have been if various different directors had made the movie. My favorite, which I still use today, was Spike Lee's Mo'hicans.  (Maybe you had to be there.)

